    "recap_headline": "Florida Atlantic University Athletics",
    "recap_text": "BOCA RATON, Fla. \u00a0\u2013\nFlorida Atlantic baseball (14-10, 1-2) dropped the series finale to UTSA (17-7, 2-1) on Sunday by an 18-8 final in seven innings.\nTHE BEGINNING\nThe teams traded the lead back and forth through the first four innings. UTSA tagged FAU freshman starter\nGarrett Grant\nfor two runs in the first inning before the Owls' offense responded in the second.\nJohn Martinez\nled off with a home run and, after an\nEli Small\nsingle and a\nPatrick Ward\ndouble,\nBrando Leroux\ntied the game with an RBI groundout. With two outs,\nMarshall Lipsey\nbeat out a ground ball to short, allowing Ward to score the go-ahead run.\nTHE TURNING POINT\nLeading 4-3 after four innings, UTSA broke the game open with six runs in the fifth. A two-run homer from Jacob Silva sparked the big inning. On in relief of Grant,\nTyler Murphy\nstruck out the next batter, but a dropped third strike and a throwing error by catcher\nIan Collier\nkept the inning at no outs. Despite not recording another hit in the inning, UTSA sent a total of 10 batters to the plate and scored four more runs to lead 10-3.\nThe Owls responded with four runs of their own in the bottom of the frame, highlighted by a three-run homer off the bat of Ward. The Roadrunners would pull away for good with seven more runs in the sixth. This time, they did it with seven hits, another Owls' error, and a hit-by-pitch.\nTHE FINISH\nWith the run-rule in play,\nMarshall Lipsey's\nsolo home run in the bottom of the sixth brought the Owls back within nine at 17-8 before UTSA added one more in the seventh and held the Owls off the board in the ensuing half-inning to end the contest in seven.\nQUOTABLE\nHead Coach\nJohn McCormack\nWe knew going in, you can't give them extra outs, and you have to make quality pitches. For the last two days, we did that, but today it got away from us. Defensively, we weren't good. We've got to regroup and be ready for Tuesday.\nTHE BATS\nWard finished 3-for-3 with a home run, a double, and a single.\nLipsey tied the team lead with his third home run of the season.\nMartinez's home run was his second of the season.\nTHE ARMS\nGrant suffered his first defeat after four innings with six runs on eight hits.\nWard also made his fourth pitching appearance of the season. He allowed one run on one hit in two-thirds of an inning.\nWHAT'S NEXT\nThe Owls return to action on Tuesday when they travel to Coral Gables for a matchup with Miami. First pitch is scheduled for 6 p.m.\nFOLLOW THE OWLS\nTo stay up to date on all things Florida Atlantic baseball, follow us on social media @faubaseball.",
    "watch_url": "https://www.espn.com/watch/"
  },
